{"title_page": "Ed Murray (Washington politician)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Edward Murray (disambiguation){{!}}Edward Murray}}\n{{Infobox office holder \n| name                = Ed Murray\n| image               = File:Ed Murray (19088884778).jpg|Ed Murray (19088884778)\n| order               = 53rd\n| office              = Mayor of Seattle\n| term_start          = January 1, 2014\n| term_end            = September 13, 2017\n| predecessor         = [[Michael McGinn]]\n| successor           = [[Bruce Harrell]]\n| state_senate1       = Washington\n| district1           = 43rd\n| term_start1         = January 2007\n| term_end1           = December 2013\n| preceded1           = [[Pat Thibaudeau]]\n| succeeded1          = [[Jamie Pedersen]]\n| state_house2        = Washington\n| district2           = 43rd\n| term_start2         = October 1995\n| term_end2           = January 2007\n| preceded2           = [[Pat Thibaudeau]]\n| succeeded2          = [[Jamie Pedersen]]\n| birth_name          = Edward Bernard Patrick Murray<ref>{{cite web|url=http://council.seattle.gov/2014/01/06/two-more-years/|title=Two More Years!|publisher=Seattle City Council|date=January 6, 2014|accessdate=April 7, 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1955|05|02}}\n| birth_place         = [[Aberdeen, Washington|Aberdeen]], [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]], U.S.\n| party               = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]\n| spouse              = {{marriage|Michael Shiosaki|2013}}\n| residence           = [[Seattle, Washington]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| alma_mater          = [[University of Portland]]\n| website             = \n}}\n[[File:Ed Murray 02.jpg|thumb|Murray, November 2014, [[Roast (comedy)|roasting]] departing ''[[The Stranger (newspaper)|Stranger]]'' reporter and editor [[Dominic Holden]]]]\n'''Edward Bernard Patrick Murray''' (born May 2, 1955) is an American politician from the state of [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]] who most recently served as the [[List of mayors of Seattle|53rd]] mayor of [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle]] from 2014 to 2017. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], he was previously a state legislator, first with the [[Washington State House of Representatives]] from 1996 to 2007, then the [[Washington State Senate]] from 2007 to 2013.\n\nIn 2017, Murray faced multiple allegations of child abuse, rape and sexual molestation, including some from family members and children under his care, all charges he denies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/seattle-mayor-ed-murray-resigns-after-fifth-child-sex-abuse-allegation/|title=Seattle Mayor Ed Murray resigns after fifth child sex-abuse allegation|date=2017-09-12|work=The Seattle Times|access-date=2017-10-02|language=en-US}}</ref> Murray resigned as mayor of Seattle on September 12, 2017.<ref name=\"Grinberg 2017\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/09/12/us/seattle-mayor-ed-murray-resigns/index.html|title=Seattle Mayor Ed Murray resigns after latest child sex-abuse allegation|last=Grinberg|first=Emanuella|date=12 September 2017|work=CNN|access-date=12 September 2017|location=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMurray was born in [[Aberdeen, Washington]], to an [[Irish Catholic]] family, and is one of seven siblings in his family. He spent much of his childhood in West Seattle's Alki neighborhood, but attended high school at [[Timberline High School (Lacey, Washington)|Timberline High School]] in [[Lacey, Washington|Lacey]], where he served as student body president.<ref name=\"SeattleTimesProfile\">[http://apps.seattletimes.com/elections/2013/general/seattle-mayoral-race/candidates/ed-murray/ 2013 Seattle mayoral race: Ed Murray], ''Seattle Times''.</ref>\n\nMurray graduated from the [[University of Portland]] in 1980; he majored in [[sociology]].<ref name=\"Kardish\">Chris Kardish, [http://www.governing.com/topics/politics/gov-seattle-ed-murray.html Ed Murray: One of America's Most Progressive Mayors], ''Governing'' (August 2015).</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nMurray began his career doing pretrial work for public defenders in [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]]. He then returned to Seattle, becoming a [[paralegal]], and quickly became active in local politics there.<ref name=\"Kardish\"/> He was [[campaign manager]] for [[Cal Anderson]], the first openly gay legislator in Washington state, in 1988 before becoming an assistant to City Councilmember [[Martha Choe]].<ref name=\"SeattleTimesProfile\"/><ref>Josh Feit, [https://www.seattlemet.com/articles/2012/12/19/the-education-of-ed-murray-january-2013 The Education of Ed Murray], ''Seattle Met'' (January 2013).</ref> Murray later managed a nonprofit focused on [[gay rights]].<ref name=\"SeattleTimesProfile\"/>\n\n===Early start===\nIn 1995, Murray, a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], ran to fill the state Senate seat left vacant by the death of Anderson, his mentor. Murray was defeated by state Representative [[Pat Thibaudeau]], but was then appointed to fill Thibaudeau's vacant state House seat in the 43rd Legislative District. He was reelected biennially until 2006, when he opted not to run for reelection to the House. The 43rd district, entirely within Seattle, includes the [[University District, Seattle, Washington|University District]], [[Montlake, Seattle, Washington|Montlake]], [[Eastlake, Seattle, Washington|Eastlake]], and [[Capitol Hill, Seattle, Washington|Capitol Hill]] neighborhoods. The district is very [[Progressivism in the United States|progressive]] and reliably Democratic{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}.\n\nIn 2006, Murray announced his intention to challenge Thibaudeau for the 43rd District seat in the [[Washington State Senate|State Senate]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Murray will leave House, run for Senate |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/politics/2002903541_murray01m.html |date=April 1, 2006 |work=[[Seattle Times]] |first=Andrew |last=Garber |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060510092924/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/politics/2002903541_murray01m.html |archivedate=2006-05-10 }}</ref> In May 2006, Thibaudeau dropped out and Murray was elected to the Senate with little opposition.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thibaudeau drops out of state senate race |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/politics/2002987690_webthibaudeau11.html |date=May 11, 2006 |work=[[Seattle Times]] | first=Ralph | last=Thomas}}</ref> He took his senate seat in January 2007. In his first session in the senate (2007\u201308), he was appointed vice chair of the majority caucus and in the 2009\u201310 session, he served as caucus chair, a post that largely is in charge of budget for the Senate and other housekeeping matters. After being reelected unopposed in 2010, Murray was appointed chair of the Ways & Means Committee for 2011\u201312.\n\nMurray previously served as chair of the House Transportation Committee.<ref>{{cite news|title=Reform sought in how state faces transportation issues|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/transportation/208206_transpo17.html?rand=68607.98 |date=January 17, 2005 |work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|first1=Jane |last1=Hadley}}</ref> He was also active in advancing [[LGBT]] rights. He led the push for an anti-discrimination law barring businesses from discriminating against gays and lesbians, a measure that finally passed in 2006 after three decades of debate.<ref>{{cite news|title=A long-awaited win for gay rights: Senate OKs state anti-bias bill|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/local/257432_gayrights28.html |date=January 28, 2006|work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|first1=Chris|last1=Mcgann}}</ref> He was also the main sponsor of legislation creating [[Domestic partnership in Washington (state)|domestic partnerships]], approved in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Washington state lawmakers pass domestic partnership bill giving rights to same-sex couples |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/04/11/america/NA-GEN-US-Domestic-Partnerships.php |date=April 11, 2007|work=[[International Herald Tribune]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Murray was the prime sponsor of a $2.4 billion Washington Senate financing bill authorizing the construction of a deep-bore tunnel underneath Seattle to replace the [[Alaskan Way Viaduct]].<ref name=\"SB 5768\">[http://app.leg.wa.gov/DLR/billsummary/default.aspx?Bill=5768&year=2009], SB 5768.</ref> Murray advocated for the project, which attracted well-documented concerns.<ref name=\"The Stranger - What Could Possibly Go Wrong?\">{{cite news|last1=Holden|first1=Dominic|title=What Could Possibly Go Wrong|url=http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/what-could-possibly-go-wrong/Content?oid=4399657||publisher=The Stranger}}</ref> Bertha, the machine drilling the deep-bore tunnel, broke down in December 2013, leading to costly delays and significant challenges such as destabilizing soil conditions under Seattle's historic [[Pioneer Square, Seattle|Pioneer Square]] and the Viaduct itself.<ref name=\"The Seattle Times - Viaduct sinks an inch as workers dig to repair Bertha\">{{cite news|last1=Lindblom|first1=Mike|title=Viaduct sinks an inch as workers dig to repair. Bertha|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2025177033_berthadifficultiesxml.html|publisher=The Seattle Times}}</ref> As of mid-2018, cost overruns on the tunnel project exceed $600 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/transportation/highway-99-tunnel-in-seattle-will-open-to-traffic-this-fall-the-state-and-contractors-say/|title=Highway 99 tunnel in Seattle will open to traffic this fall, the state and contractors say|date=11 January 2018|website=The Seattle Times}}</ref>\n\n===Mayoral career===\n[[File:Ed murray speaking 2016.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Murray speaking in 2016]]\nMurray was elected mayor of Seattle in [[Seattle mayoral election, 2013|2013]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://murray4mayor.com/ |title=Home &#124; Ed Murray for Mayor of Seattle |publisher=Murray4mayor.com |date= |accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.seattletimes.com/politicsnorthwest/2013/11/05/ballots-due-today-in-mcginn-vs-murray-showdown-for-mayor/|title= Murray: 'We're here tonight to declare victory' in mayor's race|publisher=Seattle Times|date=November 5, 2013}}</ref> He ran for [[Seattle mayoral election, 2017|reelection in 2017]], but ended his campaign on May 9 amid allegations of child sexual abuse. On September 12, 2017, amid more sexual abuse claims, Murray announced his resignation effective the next day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/seattle-mayor-ed-murray-drops-bid-for-second-term/|title= Seattle Mayor Ed Murray won't seek second term |publisher= The Seattle Times |date=May 10, 2017 |accessdate=September 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMurray is of [[Irish Catholic|Irish]] descent.<ref name=Sanders/> He is gay, and [[Coming out|came out]] in 1980.<ref name=\"SeattleTimesProfile\"/> In 2013, he married Michael Shiosaki at [[St. Mark's Episcopal Cathedral, Seattle|St. Mark's]] in Seattle; the two had been in a relationship for 22 years.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Connelly|first1=Joel|title=Ed Murray-Michael Shiosaki: A 22-year trip to the altar|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/local/connelly/article/Ed-Murray-Michael-Shiosaki-A-22-year-trip-to-4721603.php|website=SeattlePI|publisher=Hearst Seattle Media|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref> Murray did not emphasize his sexual orientation during his career, describing himself as \"a Democrat who happens to be gay.\"<ref name=\"Kardish\"/> During his campaign for the Senate, as in many of his previous campaigns, he won the backing of the [[Gay & Lesbian Victory Fund]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.advocate.com/news_detail_ektid39295.asp |title=Victory Fund endorsements yield 67 winners |work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |date=November 9, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081027021303/http://www.advocate.com/news_detail_ektid39295.asp |archivedate=October 27, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Child sexual abuse allegations==\nFive people have accused Murray of sexual abuse.<ref name=\"Grinberg 2017\"/> In April 2017, a lawsuit against Murray<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/mayor-murrays-accuser-in-sex-abuse-lawsuit-reveals-identity//|title=Local News Seattle Mayor Ed Murray's accuser in sex-abuse lawsuit reveals identity: 'I have nothing to hide'|date=2017-04-19|work=The Seattle Times|access-date=2017-04-19|language=en-US}}</ref> claimed that Murray \"raped and molested\" a teenager in 1986, paying cash for sex to a high-school dropout addicted to crack-cocaine.<ref>{{cite news|title=Suit charges sexual abuse by Seattle mayor in 1980s|date=6 April 2017|work=Seattle PI|last1=Daniel|first1=DeMay}}</ref>  Two other men made similar allegations in 2007, including a foster son who said Murray sexually assaulted him in 1984 while he was a teenager. He also spoke with a child welfare investigator and detective at the time, and persuaded the investigator that Murray had sexually abused him; however, no charges were filed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/lawsuit-alleges-seattle-mayor-ed-murray-sexually-abused-troubled-teen-in-1980s/|title=Lawsuit alleges Seattle Mayor Ed Murray sexually abused troubled teen in 1980s|date=2017-04-06|work=The Seattle Times|access-date=2017-04-06|language=en-US}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/times-watchdog/mayor-ed-murray-sexually-abused-foster-son-child-welfare-investigator-found-in-1984/|title=Seattle Mayor Ed Murray sexually abused foster son, child-welfare investigator found in 1984|author=Kamb, Lewis, and Brunner, Jim|date=July 16, 2017|work=The Seattle Times|accessdate=July 16, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170716231701/http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/times-watchdog/mayor-ed-murray-sexually-abused-foster-son-child-welfare-investigator-found-in-1984/|archivedate=July 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThrough a spokesman, Murray denied the allegations, describing them as falsehoods intended to prevent his re-election.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kiro7.com/news/local/report-lawsuit-alleges-seattle-mayor-sexually-abused-drug-addicted-teen-in-80s/509968742|title=Report: Lawsuit alleges Seattle mayor Ed Murray sexually abused drug-addicted teen in 80s|last=Staff|first=KIRO 7 News|date=2017-04-06|work=KIRO|access-date=2017-04-06|language=en-US}}</ref> Later, Murray's lawyer stated that Murray had undergone a medical examination that disproved a claim about his genitals, arguing the lawsuit should be dropped.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/mayor-ed-murrays-lawyer-medical-exam-disproves-accusers-anatomical-claim/ |author=Brunner, Jim and Lewis Kamb |title=Mayor Ed Murray's lawyer: Medical exam disproves accuser's anatomical claim |publisher=[[Seattle Times]] |date=April 11, 2017 |accessdate=April 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn September 12, 2017, Murray's cousin accused him of sexual abuse when the two teens shared a bedroom in the mid-1970s. Later that day, Murray denied the new allegation, and announced his resignation, effective the next day.<ref>{{cite news |date=September 12, 2017 |title=Seattle Mayor Ed Murray resigns after fifth child sex-abuse allegation |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/seattle-mayor-ed-murray-resigns-after-fifth-child-sex-abuse-allegation/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=September 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter his resignation, [[Amnesty International]] asked the [[Police Service of Northern Ireland]] to open an investigation into Murray's 1974 trip to [[Belfast]] and [[Wales]], which involved chaperoning 30 Catholic and Protestant children.<ref>{{cite news |last=Breen |first=Suzanne |date=September 14, 2017 |title=Ed Murray: Sex abuse claim US mayor's time in Northern Ireland 'should be probed' |url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/ed-murray-sex-abuse-claim-us-mayors-time-in-northern-ireland-should-be-probed-36130468.html |work=[[Belfast Telegraph]] |accessdate=September 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=Sanders>\n{{cite news\n | last =Sanders\n | first =Eli\n | title =Seattle's Best Christians: Senator Ed Murray\n | newspaper =The Stranger\n | location =Seattle, United States\n | pages =\n | publisher =\n | date =26 June 2012\n | url =http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/seattles-best-christians/Content?oid=14030626\n | accessdate = }}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://senatedemocrats.wa.gov/senators/murray/ Senate homepage]\n*{{C-SPAN|edmurray}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael McGinn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of mayors of Seattle|Mayor of Seattle]]|years=2014\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bruce Harrell]] (acting)}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{SeattleMayors}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Murray, Ed}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LGBT Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:LGBT mayors of places in the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT state legislators in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Washington House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Washington (state) state senators]]\n[[Category:Washington (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Seattle]]\n[[Category:University of Portland alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Aberdeen, Washington]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Timberline High School (Lacey, Washington) alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Edward Murray (disambiguation){{!}}Edward Murray}}\n{{Infobox office holder \n| name                = Ed Murray\n| image               = File:Ed Murray (19088884778).jpg|Ed Murray (19088884778)\n| order               = 53rd\n| office              = Mayor of Seattle\n| term_start          = January 1, 2014\n| term_end            = September 13, 2017\n| predecessor         = [[Michael McGinn]]\n| successor           = [[Bruce Harrell]]\n| state_senate1       = Washington\n| district1           = 43rd\n| term_start1         = January 2007\n| term_end1           = December 2013\n| preceded1           = [[Pat Thibaudeau]]\n| succeeded1          = [[Jamie Pedersen]]\n| state_house2        = Washington\n| district2           = 43rd\n| term_start2         = October 1995\n| term_end2           = January 2007\n| preceded2           = [[Pat Thibaudeau]]\n| succeeded2          = [[Jamie Pedersen]]\n| birth_name          = Edward Bernard Patrick Murray<ref>{{cite web|url=http://council.seattle.gov/2014/01/06/two-more-years/|title=Two More Years!|publisher=Seattle City Council|date=January 6, 2014|accessdate=April 7, 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1955|05|02}}\n| birth_place         = [[Aberdeen, Washington|Aberdeen]], [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]], U.S.\n| party               = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]\n| spouse              = {{marriage|Michael Shiosaki|2013}}\n| residence           = [[Seattle, Washington]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| alma_mater          = [[University of Portland]]\n| website             = \n}}\n[[File:Ed Murray 02.jpg|thumb|Murray, November 2014, [[Roast (comedy)|roasting]] departing ''[[The Stranger (newspaper)|Stranger]]'' reporter and editor [[Dominic Holden]]]]\n'''Edward Bernard Patrick Murray''' (born May 2, 1955) is an American politician from the state of [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]] who most recently served as the [[List of mayors of Seattle|53rd]] mayor of [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle]] from 2014 to 2017. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], he was previously a state legislator, first with the [[Washington State House of Representatives]] from 1996 to 2007, then the [[Washington State Senate]] from 2007 to 2013.\n\nIn 2017, Murray faced multiple allegations of child abuse, rape and sexual molestation, including some from family members and children under his care, all charges he denies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/seattle-mayor-ed-murray-resigns-after-fifth-child-sex-abuse-allegation/|title=Seattle Mayor Ed Murray resigns after fifth child sex-abuse allegation|date=2017-09-12|work=The Seattle Times|access-date=2017-10-02|language=en-US}}</ref> Murray resigned as mayor of Seattle on September 12, 2017.<ref name=\"Grinberg 2017\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/09/12/us/seattle-mayor-ed-murray-resigns/index.html|title=Seattle Mayor Ed Murray resigns after latest child sex-abuse allegation|last=Grinberg|first=Emanuella|date=12 September 2017|work=CNN|access-date=12 September 2017|location=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMurray was born in [[Aberdeen, Washington]], to an [[Irish Catholic]] family, and is one of seven siblings in his family. He spent much of his childhood in West Seattle's Alki neighborhood, but attended high school at [[Timberline High School (Lacey, Washington)|Timberline High School]] in [[Lacey, Washington|Lacey]], where he served as student body president.<ref name=\"SeattleTimesProfile\">[http://apps.seattletimes.com/elections/2013/general/seattle-mayoral-race/candidates/ed-murray/ 2013 Seattle mayoral race: Ed Murray], ''Seattle Times''.</ref>\n\nMurray graduated from the [[University of Portland]] in 1980; he majored in [[sociology]].<ref name=\"Kardish\">Chris Kardish, [http://www.governing.com/topics/politics/gov-seattle-ed-murray.html Ed Murray: One of America's Most Progressive Mayors], ''Governing'' (August 2015).</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nMurray began his career doing pretrial work for public defenders in [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]]. He then returned to Seattle, becoming a [[paralegal]], and quickly became active in local politics there.<ref name=\"Kardish\"/> He was [[campaign manager]] for [[Cal Anderson]], the first openly gay legislator in Washington state, in 1988 before becoming an assistant to City Councilmember [[Martha Choe]].<ref name=\"SeattleTimesProfile\"/><ref>Josh Feit, [https://www.seattlemet.com/articles/2012/12/19/the-education-of-ed-murray-january-2013 The Education of Ed Murray], ''Seattle Met'' (January 2013).</ref> Murray later managed a nonprofit focused on [[gay rights]].<ref name=\"SeattleTimesProfile\"/>\n\n===Early start===\nIn 1995, Murray, a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], ran to fill the state Senate seat left vacant by the death of Anderson, his mentor. Murray was defeated by state Representative [[Pat Thibaudeau]], but was then appointed to fill Thibaudeau's vacant state House seat in the 43rd Legislative District. He was reelected biennially until 2006, when he opted not to run for reelection to the House. The 43rd district, entirely within Seattle, includes the [[University District, Seattle, Washington|University District]], [[Montlake, Seattle, Washington|Montlake]], [[Eastlake, Seattle, Washington|Eastlake]], and [[Capitol Hill, Seattle, Washington|Capitol Hill]] neighborhoods. The district is very [[Progressivism in the United States|progressive]] and reliably Democratic{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}.\n\nIn 2006, Murray announced his intention to challenge Thibaudeau for the 43rd District seat in the [[Washington State Senate|State Senate]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Murray will leave House, run for Senate |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/politics/2002903541_murray01m.html |date=April 1, 2006 |work=[[Seattle Times]] |first=Andrew |last=Garber |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060510092924/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/politics/2002903541_murray01m.html |archivedate=2006-05-10 }}</ref> In May 2006, Thibaudeau dropped out and Murray was elected to the Senate with little opposition.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thibaudeau drops out of state senate race |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/politics/2002987690_webthibaudeau11.html |date=May 11, 2006 |work=[[Seattle Times]] | first=Ralph | last=Thomas}}</ref> He took his senate seat in January 2007. In his first session in the senate (2007\u201308), he was appointed vice chair of the majority caucus and in the 2009\u201310 session, he served as caucus chair, a post that largely is in charge of budget for the Senate and other housekeeping matters. After being reelected unopposed in 2010, Murray was appointed chair of the Ways & Means Committee for 2011\u201312.\n\nMurray previously served as chair of the House Transportation Committee.<ref>{{cite news|title=Reform sought in how state faces transportation issues|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/transportation/208206_transpo17.html?rand=68607.98 |date=January 17, 2005 |work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|first1=Jane |last1=Hadley}}</ref> He was also active in advancing [[LGBT]] rights. He led the push for an anti-discrimination law barring businesses from discriminating against gays and lesbians, a measure that finally passed in 2006 after three decades of debate.<ref>{{cite news|title=A long-awaited win for gay rights: Senate OKs state anti-bias bill|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/local/257432_gayrights28.html |date=January 28, 2006|work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|first1=Chris|last1=Mcgann}}</ref> He was also the main sponsor of legislation creating [[Domestic partnership in Washington (state)|domestic partnerships]], approved in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Washington state lawmakers pass domestic partnership bill giving rights to same-sex couples |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/04/11/america/NA-GEN-US-Domestic-Partnerships.php |date=April 11, 2007|work=[[International Herald Tribune]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Murray was the prime sponsor of a $2.4 billion Washington Senate financing bill authorizing the construction of a deep-bore tunnel underneath Seattle to replace the [[Alaskan Way Viaduct]].<ref name=\"SB 5768\">[http://app.leg.wa.gov/DLR/billsummary/default.aspx?Bill=5768&year=2009], SB 5768.</ref> Murray advocated for the project, which attracted well-documented concerns.<ref name=\"The Stranger - What Could Possibly Go Wrong?\">{{cite news|last1=Holden|first1=Dominic|title=What Could Possibly Go Wrong|url=http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/what-could-possibly-go-wrong/Content?oid=4399657||publisher=The Stranger}}</ref> Bertha, the machine drilling the deep-bore tunnel, broke down in December 2013, leading to costly delays and significant challenges such as destabilizing soil conditions under Seattle's historic [[Pioneer Square, Seattle|Pioneer Square]] and the Viaduct itself.<ref name=\"The Seattle Times - Viaduct sinks an inch as workers dig to repair Bertha\">{{cite news|last1=Lindblom|first1=Mike|title=Viaduct sinks an inch as workers dig to repair. Bertha|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2025177033_berthadifficultiesxml.html|publisher=The Seattle Times}}</ref> As of mid-2018, cost overruns on the tunnel project exceed $600 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/transportation/highway-99-tunnel-in-seattle-will-open-to-traffic-this-fall-the-state-and-contractors-say/|title=Highway 99 tunnel in Seattle will open to traffic this fall, the state and contractors say|date=11 January 2018|website=The Seattle Times}}</ref>\n\n===Mayoral career===\n[[File:Ed murray speaking 2016.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Murray speaking in 2016]]\nMurray was elected mayor of Seattle in [[Seattle mayoral election, 2013|2013]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://murray4mayor.com/ |title=Home &#124; Ed Murray for Mayor of Seattle |publisher=Murray4mayor.com |date= |accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.seattletimes.com/politicsnorthwest/2013/11/05/ballots-due-today-in-mcginn-vs-murray-showdown-for-mayor/|title= Murray: 'We're here tonight to declare victory' in mayor's race|publisher=Seattle Times|date=November 5, 2013}}</ref> He ran for [[Seattle mayoral election, 2017|reelection in 2017]], but ended his campaign on May 9 amid allegations of child sexual abuse. On September 12, 2017, amid more sexual abuse claims, Murray announced his resignation effective the next day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/seattle-mayor-ed-murray-drops-bid-for-second-term/|title= Seattle Mayor Ed Murray won't seek second term |publisher= The Seattle Times |date=May 10, 2017 |accessdate=September 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMurray is of [[Irish Catholic|Irish]] descent.<ref name=Sanders/> Murray is gay, and [[Coming out|came out]] in 1980.<ref name=\"SeattleTimesProfile\"/> In 2013, he married Michael Shiosaki at [[St. Mark's Episcopal Cathedral, Seattle|St. Mark's]] in Seattle; the two had been in a relationship for 22 years.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Connelly|first1=Joel|title=Ed Murray-Michael Shiosaki: A 22-year trip to the altar|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/local/connelly/article/Ed-Murray-Michael-Shiosaki-A-22-year-trip-to-4721603.php|website=SeattlePI|publisher=Hearst Seattle Media|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref> Murray has not emphasized his sexual orientation during his career, describing himself as \"a Democrat who happens to be gay.\"<ref name=\"Kardish\"/> During his campaign to the Senate, as in many of his previous campaigns, he won the backing of the [[Gay & Lesbian Victory Fund]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.advocate.com/news_detail_ektid39295.asp |title=Victory Fund endorsements yield 67 winners |work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |date=November 9, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081027021303/http://www.advocate.com/news_detail_ektid39295.asp |archivedate=October 27, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Child sexual abuse allegations==\nFive people have accused Murray of sexual abuse.<ref name=\"Grinberg 2017\"/> In April 2017, a lawsuit against Murray<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/mayor-murrays-accuser-in-sex-abuse-lawsuit-reveals-identity//|title=Local News Seattle Mayor Ed Murray's accuser in sex-abuse lawsuit reveals identity: 'I have nothing to hide'|date=2017-04-19|work=The Seattle Times|access-date=2017-04-19|language=en-US}}</ref> claimed that Murray \"raped and molested\" a teenager in 1986, paying cash for sex to a high-school dropout addicted to crack-cocaine.<ref>{{cite news|title=Suit charges sexual abuse by Seattle mayor in 1980s|date=6 April 2017|work=Seattle PI|last1=Daniel|first1=DeMay}}</ref>  Two other men made similar allegations in 2007, including a foster son who said Murray sexually assaulted him in 1984 while he was a teenager. He also spoke with a child welfare investigator and detective at the time, and persuaded the investigator that Murray had sexually abused him; however, no charges were filed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/lawsuit-alleges-seattle-mayor-ed-murray-sexually-abused-troubled-teen-in-1980s/|title=Lawsuit alleges Seattle Mayor Ed Murray sexually abused troubled teen in 1980s|date=2017-04-06|work=The Seattle Times|access-date=2017-04-06|language=en-US}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/times-watchdog/mayor-ed-murray-sexually-abused-foster-son-child-welfare-investigator-found-in-1984/|title=Seattle Mayor Ed Murray sexually abused foster son, child-welfare investigator found in 1984|author=Kamb, Lewis, and Brunner, Jim|date=July 16, 2017|work=The Seattle Times|accessdate=July 16, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170716231701/http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/times-watchdog/mayor-ed-murray-sexually-abused-foster-son-child-welfare-investigator-found-in-1984/|archivedate=July 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThrough a spokesman, Murray denied the allegations, describing them as falsehoods intended to prevent his re-election.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kiro7.com/news/local/report-lawsuit-alleges-seattle-mayor-sexually-abused-drug-addicted-teen-in-80s/509968742|title=Report: Lawsuit alleges Seattle mayor Ed Murray sexually abused drug-addicted teen in 80s|last=Staff|first=KIRO 7 News|date=2017-04-06|work=KIRO|access-date=2017-04-06|language=en-US}}</ref> Later, Murray's lawyer stated that Murray had undergone a medical examination that disproved a claim about his genitals, arguing the lawsuit should be dropped.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/mayor-ed-murrays-lawyer-medical-exam-disproves-accusers-anatomical-claim/ |author=Brunner, Jim and Lewis Kamb |title=Mayor Ed Murray's lawyer: Medical exam disproves accuser's anatomical claim |publisher=[[Seattle Times]] |date=April 11, 2017 |accessdate=April 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn September 12, 2017, Murray's cousin accused him of sexual abuse when the two teens shared a bedroom in the mid-1970s. Later that day, Murray denied the new allegation, and announced his resignation, effective the next day.<ref>{{cite news |date=September 12, 2017 |title=Seattle Mayor Ed Murray resigns after fifth child sex-abuse allegation |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/seattle-mayor-ed-murray-resigns-after-fifth-child-sex-abuse-allegation/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=September 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter his resignation, [[Amnesty International]] asked the [[Police Service of Northern Ireland]] to open an investigation into Murray's 1974 trip to [[Belfast]] and [[Wales]], which involved chaperoning 30 Catholic and Protestant children.<ref>{{cite news |last=Breen |first=Suzanne |date=September 14, 2017 |title=Ed Murray: Sex abuse claim US mayor's time in Northern Ireland 'should be probed' |url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/ed-murray-sex-abuse-claim-us-mayors-time-in-northern-ireland-should-be-probed-36130468.html |work=[[Belfast Telegraph]] |accessdate=September 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=Sanders>\n{{cite news\n | last =Sanders\n | first =Eli\n | title =Seattle's Best Christians: Senator Ed Murray\n | newspaper =The Stranger\n | location =Seattle, United States\n | pages =\n | publisher =\n | date =26 June 2012\n | url =http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/seattles-best-christians/Content?oid=14030626\n | accessdate = }}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://senatedemocrats.wa.gov/senators/murray/ Senate homepage]\n*{{C-SPAN|edmurray}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael McGinn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of mayors of Seattle|Mayor of Seattle]]|years=2014\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bruce Harrell]] (acting)}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{SeattleMayors}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Murray, Ed}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LGBT Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:LGBT mayors of places in the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT state legislators in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Washington House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Washington (state) state senators]]\n[[Category:Washington (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Seattle]]\n[[Category:University of Portland alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Aberdeen, Washington]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Timberline High School (Lacey, Washington) alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Wukai", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ed_Murray_(Washington_politician)"}
