{"title_page": "Angophora hispida", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{speciesbox\n|name = Dwarf apple\n|image = Angophora hispida-Minchen.jpg\n|genus = Angophora\n|species = hispida\n|authority = ([[James Edward Smith|Sm.]]) [[Donald Frederick Blaxell|Blaxell]]<ref name=apni/>\n|synonyms = Eucalyptus hispida ([[Sm.]]) [[Murray Ian Hill Brooker|Brooker]]<br />''Angophora cordifolia'' [[Cav.]]\n|range_map = Angophora hispida DistMap.png\n|range_map_caption = Occurrence data from [[Australasian Virtual Herbarium|AVH]]\n}}\n\n'''''Angophora hispida''''' grows as a [[Mallee (habit)|mallee]], or as a tree to about 7&nbsp;m (25&nbsp;ft) in height.<ref name='nswflo'>{{NSW Flora Online|author=K. Hill|genus=Angophora|species=hispida}}</ref>\n''A. hispida'''s small size, especially when compared to its ''[[Angophora]]'' and ''[[Eucalyptus]]'' relatives, leads to it being known by the common name '''dwarf apple'''.<ref name=apni>{{APNI | name = ''Angophora hispida''  (Sm.) Blaxell| id = 37817}}</ref> It is native to a relatively small patch of central [[New South Wales]] \u2013 from just south of [[Sydney]] up to the [[Gosford]] area. The plant's leaves are [[Sessility (botany)|sessile]] (stalk-less) and hug the stem with heart-shaped bases. Its previous name \u2013 ''A. cordifolia'' \u2013 referred to these [[Cordate (leaf shape)|cordate]] leaves. Another distinctive feature are the red bristly hairs that cover the branchlets, flower bases and new growth. This leads to the specific epithet ''hispida'' (meaning \"bristly\").\n\n==Taxonomy==\nCommon names include dwarf apple and scrub apple,<ref name=Ben98>{{cite journal |last=Benson |first=Doug |author2=McDougall, Lyn |year=1998|title=Ecology of Sydney plant species:Part 6 Dicotyledon family Myrtaceae |journal=Cunninghamia |volume=5 |issue=4 |pages=809\u2013987 |id= |url=http://www.rbgsyd.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0008/58049/Cun5Ben808.pdf}}</ref> and ''banda'' in the [[Cadigal]] language.<ref name=\"floransw\">{{NSW Flora Online|genus=Angophora |species=hispida|author=Hill, Ken}}</ref>\n\n[[Loddiges|Loddiges Nursery]] called it the Rough Metrosideros<ref name=met/> after the dwarf apple was described by [[James Edward Smith]] in 1797 as ''Metrosideros hispida'', having been collected by Surgeon-General of New South Wales, [[John White (surgeon)|John White]] in 1795.<ref name=met>{{APNI | name = ''Metrosideros hispida'' Sm. | id = 10934}}</ref> [[Antonio Jos\u00e9 Cavanilles]] also described it the same year as ''Angophora cordifolia'', having been collected somewhere near the shoreline in Port Jackson.<ref>{{APNI | name = ''Angophora cordifolia'' Cav. | id = 37754}}</ref> The latter name remained in use until 1976, when ''A. hispida'' was erected by Don Blaxell,<ref>{{APNI | name = ''Angophora hispida'' (Sm.) Blaxell | id = 37817}}</ref>  who had established that Smith's name had been published four months earlier in May (contrasting with Cavanillles in September) of 1797.<ref name=blaxell76>{{cite journal|last=Blaxell|first=Don F.|year=1976|title=Angophora hispida, a New Name for A. cordifolia (Myrtaceae)|journal=Kew Bulletin|volume=31|issue=2|pages=272|jstor=4109173|doi=10.2307/4109173}}</ref>\n\nSmith had been sent a specimen by Surgeon-General White, which flowered in 1798. He went on to publish a fuller description accompanied by an illustration by [[James Sowerby]] in 1805.<ref name=blaxell76/>\n\n[[Kevin Thiele]] and [[Pauline Ladiges]] published a phylogenetic study based on morphology and came up with the smudgy apple (''[[Angophora woodsiana]]'') as the dwarf apple's closest relative.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Thiele | first1 = Kevin | last2 = Ladiges | first2 = Pauline Y. | doi = 10.1111/j.1096-0031.1988.tb00466.x | title = A Cladistic Analysis of ''Angophora'' Cav. (Myrtaceae) | journal = Cladistics | volume = 4 |issue = 1| pages = 23\u201342 | year = 1988 | pmid =  | pmc = }}</ref> Brooker and colleagues consider it to be more closely related to the broad-leaved apple (''[[Angophora subvelutina|A. subvelutina]]'').<ref name=\"euclid\"/>\n\nMore recently, genetic work has been published showing ''Angophora'' to be more closely related to ''Eucalyptus'' than ''[[Corymbia]]'', and the name ''Eucalyptus hispida'' has been proposed for this species if it were to be placed in the eucalypt genus.<ref>{{APNI | name = ''Eucalyptus hispida'' (Sm.) Brooker | id = 224036}}</ref>\n\nHybrids with ''[[Angophora costata]]'' and ''[[Angophora bakeri|A. bakeri]]'' have been recorded.<ref name=Ben98/>\n\n==Description==\nThe dwarf apple grows as a small tree or mallee to 7&nbsp;m (25&nbsp;ft) high. It has greyish flaky bark.<ref name=\"floransw\"/> Like other members of the genus ''Angophora'' and unlike other eucalypts, the leaves are arranged oppositely along the stem.<ref name=Fairley>{{cite book |author1=Fairley, Alan |author2=Moore, Philip |title=Native Plants of the Sydney District:An Identification Guide |year=2000 |edition= 2nd|publisher=Kangaroo Press |pages=194\u201395 |location=Kenthurst, NSW |isbn=0-7318-1031-7}}</ref> Sitting on petiole 0\u20134&nbsp;mm long, the leaves are ovate to elliptic in shape, and measure 5\u201310&nbsp;cm (2\u20134&nbsp;in) in length and 3\u20134.5&nbsp;cm (1.2\u20131.8&nbsp;in) across, with a blunt rounded apex, and a cordate (heart-shaped) base.<ref name=\"floransw\"/> They are a pale yellow-green above and greyish on their undersurface.<ref name=Fairley/> New growth is covered in reddish hairs.<ref name=Fairley/> Flowering takes place from November to January.<ref name=Ben98/> The showy creamy-white flower heads are terminal and [[umbel]]late, each composed of three to seven flowers on 0.8\u20133.2&nbsp;cm (0.3\u20131.3&nbsp;in) long [[Pedicel (botany)|pedicels]], which in turn branch off from a 1.5\u20137&nbsp;cm (0.6\u20132.8&nbsp;in) long [[Peduncle (botany)|peduncle]]. Like the new leaves and stems, developing buds are covered in reddish hair. Globular in shape with longitudinal ribbing, they grow to a diameter of 0.9\u20131.3&nbsp;cm (0.4\u20130.5&nbsp;in).<ref name=\"euclid\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anbg.gov.au/cpbr/cd-keys/euclid3/euclidsample/html/Angophora_hispida.htm|title=Fact Sheet: ''Angophora hispida''|author1=Slee, A.V. |author2=Brooker, M.I.H. |author3=Duffy, S.M. |author4=West, J.G. |year=2006|work=EUCLID: Eucalypts of Australia|publisher=CSIRO Publishing|accessdate=9 December 2012|location=Collingwood, Victoria}}</ref>\n\nThe flowers fall leaving the cup-shaped woody seed pods or fruit, which measure 1.5\u20132.6&nbsp;cm (0.6\u20130.8&nbsp;in) long and 1.3\u20132&nbsp;cm (0.5\u20130.6&nbsp;in) in diameter.<ref name=\"euclid\"/> These shed the mature seed in February and March.<ref name=Ben98/> The oval-shaped seeds are brown and flat, measuring 0.8\u20131&nbsp;cm (0.3\u20130.4&nbsp;in) long.<ref name=\"euclid\"/>\n==Gallery==\n<gallery heights=\"130px\" mode=packed-hover style=\"margin-top:3em;\">\nAngophora hispida DSC 4503 (27666550975).jpg|Opposite & decussate leaves\nAngophora hispida Dwarf apple (Angophora hispida) 31-10-2007 IMG 5392 (1807217983).jpg|(After fire) red hairy new growth\nAngophora hispida DSC 6592 (33368522242).jpg|Ribbed nuts\nAngophora hispida Angophora hispida DSC 0287 (6747735393).jpg|Flowers & new leaves\nAngophora hispida Buds 44670772685 d40aeff6c8 o.jpg|Red, hairy flower buds\n</gallery>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe dwarf apple is found only in the Sydney Basin, as far south as O\u2019Hares Creek off the [[Georges River]], on dry sandstone soils low in nutrients. The associated plant communities are heath, scrubland or open woodland, with such species as scribbly gums (''[[Eucalyptus racemosa]]'' and ''[[Eucalyptus haemastoma|E. haemastoma]]''), red bloodwood (''[[Corymbia gummifera]]''),  narrow-leaved apple (''[[Angophora bakeri]]'') heath banksia (''[[Banksia ericifolia]]''), rusty banksia (''[[Banksia oblongifolia|B. oblongifolia]]''), silver banksia (''[[Banksia marginata|B. marginata]]''), conesticks (''[[Petrophile pulchella]]''), scrub sheoak (''[[Allocasuarina distyla]]''), wax flower (''[[Eriostemon australasius]]'') and parrot pea (''[[Dillwynia floribunda]]'').<ref name=Ben98/> It grows from sea level to an altitude of 300&nbsp;m (1000&nbsp;ft) and with an annual rainfall of 800 to 1600&nbsp;mm (30 to 60 in).<ref name=Ben98/>\n\n==Ecology==\n[[File:Angophora hispida beetles 2 orig.JPG|thumb|right|Insects foraging among the flowerheads]]\nThe dwarf apple regenerates from bushfire by resprouting from its woody base, known as a [[lignotuber]], or epicormic shoots. It can flower within a year of being burnt and plays an important role as a food source for nectar-eating insects after bushfire.<ref name=Ben98/>\n\nThe flowers attract birds such as the [[noisy miner]] and [[wattlebird]]s and a wide variety of insects, including honeybees, native bees, flies, moths and butterflies, and a wide array of beetles, including the rose chafer (''[[Eupoecila australasiae]]''), green-velvet flower chafer (''[[Glycyphana brunnipes]]''), the variable jewel beetle (''[[Temognatha variabilis]]''), the cowboy beetle (''[[Chondropyga dorsalis]]''), and a scarab beetle ''[[Bisallardiana gymnopleura]]'', as well as members of the scarab genus ''[[Phyllotocus]]'' and [[soldier beetle]] genus ''[[Telephorus]]''.<ref name=Ben98/>\n\nThe dwarf apple is a host for larvae of [[froghopper]]s, known as spittlebugs.<ref name=Ben98/>\n\n''Angophora hispida'' has been recorded as a host for the mistletoe species ''[[Muellerina eucalyptoides]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Downey|first=Paul O.|year=1998|title=An inventory of host species for each aerial mistletoe species (Loranthaceae and Viscaceae) in Australia|journal=Cunninghamia|volume=5|issue=3|pages=685\u2013720|url=https://www.rbgsyd.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0018/58041/Cun5Dow685.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Cultivation==\nThis is a small tree suitable for larger gardens, its red new growth and profuse white flowers are attractive horticultural features. Flowering in summer, the flowers attract brightly coloured beetles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anbg.gov.au/gnp/gnp6/ang-hisp.html |title=Growing Native Plants: 'Angophora hispida'' |accessdate=9 December 2012 |author=ANBG Staff |year=2002 |work=Australian National Botanic Gardens Website |publisher=ANBG}}</ref> It requires a sunny aspect and good drainage to grow well.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n== External links ==\n* [http://avh.ala.org.au/occurrences/search?taxa=Angophora+hispida#tab_mapView The Australasian Virtual Herbarium \u2013 Occurrence data for ''Angophora hispida'']\n*{{Commons category inline|Angophora hispida}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q4564065}}\n\n[[Category:Angophora|hispida]]\n[[Category:Flora of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Trees of Australia]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of Australia]]\n[[Category:Ornamental trees]]\n[[Category:Mallees (habit)]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{speciesbox\n|name = Dwarf apple\n|image = Angophora hispida-Minchen.jpg\n|genus = Angophora\n|species = hispida\n|authority = ([[James Edward Smith|Sm.]]) [[Donald Frederick Blaxell|Blaxell]]<ref name=apni/>\n|synonyms = Eucalyptus hispida ([[Sm.]]) [[Murray Ian Hill Brooker|Brooker]]<br />''Angophora cordifolia'' [[Cav.]]\n|range_map = Angophora hispida DistMap.png\n|range_map_caption = Occurrence data from [[Australasian Virtual Herbarium|AVH]]\n}}\n\n'''''Angophora hispida''''' grows as a [[Mallee (habit)|mallee]], or as a tree to about 7&nbsp;m (25&nbsp;ft) in height.<ref name='nswflo'>{{NSW Flora Online|author=K. Hill|genus=Angophora|species=hispida}}</ref>\n''A. hispida'''s small size, especially when compared to its ''[[Angophora]]'' and ''[[Eucalyptus]]'' relatives, leads to it being known by the common name '''dwarf apple'''.<ref name=apni>{{APNI | name = ''Angophora hispida''  (Sm.) Blaxell| id = 37817}}</ref> It is native to a relatively small patch of central [[New South Wales]] \u2013 from just south of [[Sydney]] up to the [[Gosford]] area. The plant's leaves are [[Sessility (botany)|sessile]] (stalk-less) and hug the stem with heart-shaped bases. Its previous name \u2013 ''A. cordifolia'' \u2013 referred to these [[Cordate (leaf shape)|cordate]] leaves. Another distinctive feature are the red bristly hairs that cover the branchlets, flower bases and new growth. This leads to the specific epithet ''hispida'' (meaning \"bristly\").\n\n==Taxonomy==\nCommon names include dwarf apple and scrub apple,<ref name=Ben98>{{cite journal |last=Benson |first=Doug |author2=McDougall, Lyn |year=1998|title=Ecology of Sydney plant species:Part 6 Dicotyledon family Myrtaceae |journal=Cunninghamia |volume=5 |issue=4 |pages=809\u2013987 |id= |url=http://www.rbgsyd.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0008/58049/Cun5Ben808.pdf}}</ref> and ''banda'' in the [[Cadigal]] language.<ref name=\"floransw\">{{NSW Flora Online|genus=Angophora |species=hispida|author=Hill, Ken}}</ref>\n\n[[Loddiges|Loddiges Nursery]] called it the Rough Metrosideros<ref name=met/> after the dwarf apple was described by [[James Edward Smith]] in 1797 as ''Metrosideros hispida'', having been collected by Surgeon-General of New South Wales, [[John White (surgeon)|John White]] in 1795.<ref name=met>{{APNI | name = ''Metrosideros hispida'' Sm. | id = 10934}}</ref> [[Antonio Jos\u00e9 Cavanilles]] also described it the same year as ''Angophora cordifolia'', having been collected somewhere near the shoreline in Port Jackson.<ref>{{APNI | name = ''Angophora cordifolia'' Cav. | id = 37754}}</ref> The latter name remained in use until 1976, when ''A. hispida'' was erected by Don Blaxell,<ref>{{APNI | name = ''Angophora hispida'' (Sm.) Blaxell | id = 37817}}</ref>  who had established that Smith's name had been published four months earlier in May (contrasting with Cavanillles in September) of 1797.<ref name=blaxell76>{{cite journal|last=Blaxell|first=Don F.|year=1976|title=Angophora hispida, a New Name for A. cordifolia (Myrtaceae)|journal=Kew Bulletin|volume=31|issue=2|pages=272|jstor=4109173|doi=10.2307/4109173}}</ref>\n\nSmith had been sent a specimen by Surgeon-General White, which flowered in 1798. He went on to publish a fuller description accompanied by an illustration by [[James Sowerby]] in 1805.<ref name=blaxell76/>\n\n[[Kevin Thiele]] and Pauline Ladiges published a phylogenetic study based on morphology and came up with the smudgy apple (''[[Angophora woodsiana]]'') as the dwarf apple's closest relative.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Thiele | first1 = Kevin | last2 = Ladiges | first2 = Pauline Y. | doi = 10.1111/j.1096-0031.1988.tb00466.x | title = A Cladistic Analysis of ''Angophora'' Cav. (Myrtaceae) | journal = Cladistics | volume = 4 |issue = 1| pages = 23\u201342 | year = 1988 | pmid =  | pmc = }}</ref> Brooker and colleagues consider it to be more closely related to the broad-leaved apple (''[[Angophora subvelutina|A. subvelutina]]'').<ref name=\"euclid\"/>\n\nMore recently, genetic work has been published showing ''Angophora'' to be more closely related to ''Eucalyptus'' than ''[[Corymbia]]'', and the name ''Eucalyptus hispida'' has been proposed for this species if it were to be placed in the eucalypt genus.<ref>{{APNI | name = ''Eucalyptus hispida'' (Sm.) Brooker | id = 224036}}</ref>\n\nHybrids with ''[[Angophora costata]]'' and ''[[Angophora bakeri|A. bakeri]]'' have been recorded.<ref name=Ben98/>\n\n==Description==\nThe dwarf apple grows as a small tree or mallee to 7&nbsp;m (25&nbsp;ft) high. It has greyish flaky bark.<ref name=\"floransw\"/> Like other members of the genus ''Angophora'' and unlike other eucalypts, the leaves are arranged oppositely along the stem.<ref name=Fairley>{{cite book |author1=Fairley, Alan |author2=Moore, Philip |title=Native Plants of the Sydney District:An Identification Guide |year=2000 |edition= 2nd|publisher=Kangaroo Press |pages=194\u201395 |location=Kenthurst, NSW |isbn=0-7318-1031-7}}</ref> Sitting on petiole 0\u20134&nbsp;mm long, the leaves are ovate to elliptic in shape, and measure 5\u201310&nbsp;cm (2\u20134&nbsp;in) in length and 3\u20134.5&nbsp;cm (1.2\u20131.8&nbsp;in) across, with a blunt rounded apex, and a cordate (heart-shaped) base.<ref name=\"floransw\"/> They are a pale yellow-green above and greyish on their undersurface.<ref name=Fairley/> New growth is covered in reddish hairs.<ref name=Fairley/> Flowering takes place from November to January.<ref name=Ben98/> The showy creamy-white flower heads are terminal and [[umbel]]late, each composed of three to seven flowers on 0.8\u20133.2&nbsp;cm (0.3\u20131.3&nbsp;in) long [[Pedicel (botany)|pedicels]], which in turn branch off from a 1.5\u20137&nbsp;cm (0.6\u20132.8&nbsp;in) long [[Peduncle (botany)|peduncle]]. Like the new leaves and stems, developing buds are covered in reddish hair. Globular in shape with longitudinal ribbing, they grow to a diameter of 0.9\u20131.3&nbsp;cm (0.4\u20130.5&nbsp;in).<ref name=\"euclid\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anbg.gov.au/cpbr/cd-keys/euclid3/euclidsample/html/Angophora_hispida.htm|title=Fact Sheet: ''Angophora hispida''|author1=Slee, A.V. |author2=Brooker, M.I.H. |author3=Duffy, S.M. |author4=West, J.G. |year=2006|work=EUCLID: Eucalypts of Australia|publisher=CSIRO Publishing|accessdate=9 December 2012|location=Collingwood, Victoria}}</ref>\n\nThe flowers fall leaving the cup-shaped woody seed pods or fruit, which measure 1.5\u20132.6&nbsp;cm (0.6\u20130.8&nbsp;in) long and 1.3\u20132&nbsp;cm (0.5\u20130.6&nbsp;in) in diameter.<ref name=\"euclid\"/> These shed the mature seed in February and March.<ref name=Ben98/> The oval-shaped seeds are brown and flat, measuring 0.8\u20131&nbsp;cm (0.3\u20130.4&nbsp;in) long.<ref name=\"euclid\"/>\n==Gallery==\n<gallery heights=\"130px\" mode=packed-hover style=\"margin-top:3em;\">\nAngophora hispida DSC 4503 (27666550975).jpg|Opposite & decussate leaves\nAngophora hispida Dwarf apple (Angophora hispida) 31-10-2007 IMG 5392 (1807217983).jpg|(After fire) red hairy new growth\nAngophora hispida DSC 6592 (33368522242).jpg|Ribbed nuts\nAngophora hispida Angophora hispida DSC 0287 (6747735393).jpg|Flowers & new leaves\nAngophora hispida Buds 44670772685 d40aeff6c8 o.jpg|Red, hairy flower buds\n</gallery>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe dwarf apple is found only in the Sydney Basin, as far south as O\u2019Hares Creek off the [[Georges River]], on dry sandstone soils low in nutrients. The associated plant communities are heath, scrubland or open woodland, with such species as scribbly gums (''[[Eucalyptus racemosa]]'' and ''[[Eucalyptus haemastoma|E. haemastoma]]''), red bloodwood (''[[Corymbia gummifera]]''),  narrow-leaved apple (''[[Angophora bakeri]]'') heath banksia (''[[Banksia ericifolia]]''), rusty banksia (''[[Banksia oblongifolia|B. oblongifolia]]''), silver banksia (''[[Banksia marginata|B. marginata]]''), conesticks (''[[Petrophile pulchella]]''), scrub sheoak (''[[Allocasuarina distyla]]''), wax flower (''[[Eriostemon australasius]]'') and parrot pea (''[[Dillwynia floribunda]]'').<ref name=Ben98/> It grows from sea level to an altitude of 300&nbsp;m (1000&nbsp;ft) and with an annual rainfall of 800 to 1600&nbsp;mm (30 to 60 in).<ref name=Ben98/>\n\n==Ecology==\n[[File:Angophora hispida beetles 2 orig.JPG|thumb|right|Insects foraging among the flowerheads]]\nThe dwarf apple regenerates from bushfire by resprouting from its woody base, known as a [[lignotuber]], or epicormic shoots. It can flower within a year of being burnt and plays an important role as a food source for nectar-eating insects after bushfire.<ref name=Ben98/>\n\nThe flowers attract birds such as the [[noisy miner]] and [[wattlebird]]s and a wide variety of insects, including honeybees, native bees, flies, moths and butterflies, and a wide array of beetles, including the rose chafer (''[[Eupoecila australasiae]]''), green-velvet flower chafer (''[[Glycyphana brunnipes]]''), the variable jewel beetle (''[[Temognatha variabilis]]''), the cowboy beetle (''[[Chondropyga dorsalis]]''), and a scarab beetle ''[[Bisallardiana gymnopleura]]'', as well as members of the scarab genus ''[[Phyllotocus]]'' and [[soldier beetle]] genus ''[[Telephorus]]''.<ref name=Ben98/>\n\nThe dwarf apple is a host for larvae of [[froghopper]]s, known as spittlebugs.<ref name=Ben98/>\n\n''Angophora hispida'' has been recorded as a host for the mistletoe species ''[[Muellerina eucalyptoides]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Downey|first=Paul O.|year=1998|title=An inventory of host species for each aerial mistletoe species (Loranthaceae and Viscaceae) in Australia|journal=Cunninghamia|volume=5|issue=3|pages=685\u2013720|url=https://www.rbgsyd.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0018/58041/Cun5Dow685.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Cultivation==\nThis is a small tree suitable for larger gardens, its red new growth and profuse white flowers are attractive horticultural features. Flowering in summer, the flowers attract brightly coloured beetles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anbg.gov.au/gnp/gnp6/ang-hisp.html |title=Growing Native Plants: 'Angophora hispida'' |accessdate=9 December 2012 |author=ANBG Staff |year=2002 |work=Australian National Botanic Gardens Website |publisher=ANBG}}</ref> It requires a sunny aspect and good drainage to grow well.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n== External links ==\n* [http://avh.ala.org.au/occurrences/search?taxa=Angophora+hispida#tab_mapView The Australasian Virtual Herbarium \u2013 Occurrence data for ''Angophora hispida'']\n*{{Commons category inline|Angophora hispida}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q4564065}}\n\n[[Category:Angophora|hispida]]\n[[Category:Flora of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Trees of Australia]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of Australia]]\n[[Category:Ornamental trees]]\n[[Category:Mallees (habit)]]\n", "name_user": "Gderrin", "label": "safe", "comment": "add link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angophora_hispida"}
{"title_page": "Ancyroclepsis rhodoconia", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = \n| image_caption = \n| image2 = \n| image2_caption = \n| genus = Ancyroclepsis\n| species = rhodoconia\n| authority = [[Alexey Diakonoff|Diakonoff]], 1976\n| synonyms = \n}}\n'''''Ancyroclepsis rhodoconia''''' is a [[moth]] of the family [[Tortricidae]]. It is found in [[Nepal]], [[China]] (Likiang) and [[Vietnam]].<ref>[https://www.redalyc.org/pdf/455/45512048004.pdf Tortricidae from Vietnam in the collection of the Berlin Museum. 5. Archipini and Sparganothini (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae)]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q4753271}}\n\n[[Category:Moths described in 1976]]\n[[Category:Archipini]]\n[[Category:Moths of Asia]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Alexey Diakonoff]]\n\n\n{{Archipini-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = \n| image_caption = \n| image2 = \n| image2_caption = \n| genus = Ancyroclepsis\n| species = rhodoconia\n| authority = [[Alexey Diakonoff|Diakonoff]], 1976\n| synonyms = \n}}\n'''''Ancyroclepsis rhodoconia''''' is a [[moth]] of the family [[Tortricidae]]. It is found in [[Nepal]], [[China]] (Likiang) and [[Vietnam]].<ref>[http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/pdf/455/45512048004.pdf Tortricidae from Vietnam in the collection of the Berlin Museum. 5. Archipini and Sparganothini (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae)]{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q4753271}}\n\n[[Category:Moths described in 1976]]\n[[Category:Archipini]]\n[[Category:Moths of Asia]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Alexey Diakonoff]]\n\n\n{{Archipini-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Logan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:bad link repair, replaced: http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/ \u2192 https://www.redalyc.org/", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancyroclepsis_rhodoconia"}
{"title_page": "Ryan Ward (lacrosse)", "text_new": "{{Infobox lacrosse player\n| name = Ryan Ward\n| image = Ryan Ward.jpg \n| image_size = \n| position = Forward \n| shoots = Right\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 9\n| weight_lbs = 190\n| ncaa_team = [[Butler University]]\n| former_nll_teams = [[Edmonton Rush]]<br>[[Minnesota Swarm]]<br>[[Philadelphia Wings (1987\u20132014)|Philadelphia Wings]]\n| former_mll_teams = [[Rochester Rattlers]]\n| mll_team = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1980|9|26|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]], [[British Columbia|BC]], [[Canada|CAN]]\n| nationality = Canada\n| nll_draft = 3rd overall\n| nll_draft_year = 2003\n| nll_draft_team = [[Philadelphia Wings (1987\u20132014)|Philadelphia Wings]]\n| career_start = [[2004 NLL season|2004]]\n| career_end = [[2014 NLL season|2014]]\n| nickname = Wardo\n}}\n'''Ryan Ward''' (born September 26, 1980) is a former [[lacrosse]] player in the [[National Lacrosse League]]. Ward played 11 seasons in the NLL with the [[Philadelphia Wings (1987\u20132014)|Philadelphia Wings]], [[Minnesota Swarm]], and [[Edmonton Rush]]. He retired after the 2014 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pointstreaksites.com/view/nll/news-1147/news_258208|work=NLL web site|date=December 8, 2014|accessdate=March 18, 2015|title=Black Wolves ready for first year at Mohegan Sun}}</ref>\n\nWard is a two-time [[Mann Cup]] winner (in 2003 and 2005) with the [[Victoria Shamrocks]] of the [[Western Lacrosse Association]]. In 2003, he was awarded the Western Lacrosse Association MVP award. Ward was also a junior high Physical Education teacher in Owatonna, Minnesota. He is also the founder of Twin Cities Lacrosse; a lacrosse club based in the southwest metro area of Minnesota.\n\n==Beginning and overview==\nWard has been playing lacrosse since the age of three. For the last 25 years, he has played in top indoor and outdoor leagues across North America. He has spent most of his free time coaching youth lacrosse camps and clinics throughout the Twin Cities. Ward currently resides in Chanhassen, Minnesota. He is also the Varsity Head Coach of the Eden Prairie High School lacrosse team. Ryan ward is an amazing coach and is good at lacrosse and is a pretty cool cat with a shlanker\n\n==College career==\nWard is a graduate of [[Butler University]]. As a senior, he was named Team Captain, and still holds the school record for assists.\n\n==Professional career==\nWard was selected by the [[Rochester Rattlers]] of [[Major League Lacrosse]] as a first-round selection (2nd overall) in the 2004 [[MLL Collegiate Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swarmitup.com/RyanWard.htm|title=44 - Ryan Ward|publisher=swarmitup.com|access-date=August 25, 2019}}</ref> He played one season in the league.\n\nThe [[Philadelphia Wings (1987\u20132014)|Philadelphia Wings]] drafted Ward in the first round (3rd overall) in the [[National Lacrosse League entry draft#2003 NLL|2003 NLL Entry Draft]].<ref name = swarm>{{cite web |url=http://www.mnswarm.com/team/player.asp?player_id=34|title=Ryan Ward Minnesota Swarm Player Bio |accessdate=2008-02-06|date=|work=MNSwarm.com}}</ref>  As a rookie, he was awarded Rookie of the Week honors in week 8 of the season and named to the 2004 NLL All-Rookie Team. During the [[2005 NLL season]], Ward was traded to the [[Minnesota Swarm]]. In the [[2006 NLL season]], he was awarded Offensive Player of the Week honors in week 12 for his ten-point game against the [[Portland LumberJax]], and helped lead the Swarm to their first playoff appearance.<ref name = swarm/>  In [[2007 NLL season|2007]], he was elected to his first [[National Lacrosse League All-Star Game]] and again helped lead his team back to the playoffs. In [[2008 NLL season|2008]], Ward was again named to the All-Star team, replacing the injured [[Casey Powell]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nll.com/article.php?id=3369|work=NLL.com|title=All-Star Weekend: Roster Updates|date=March 15, 2008|accessdate=2008-03-15}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n===NLL===\n{| BORDER=\"0\" CELLPADDING=\"3\" CELLSPACING=\"0\"\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! colspan=\"6\" | Regular&nbsp;Season\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! colspan=\"6\" | Playoffs\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! Season !! Team !! GP !! G !! A !! Pts !! LB !! PIM !! GP !! G !! A !! Pts !! LB !! PIM\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 2004 || Philadelphia || 13 ||\t18 || 19 || 37 || 45 || 0 || -- || -- || -- || -- || -- || --\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| 2005 || Philadelphia || 5 || 5 || 2 || 7 || 23 || 2 || -- || -- || -- || -- || -- || --\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| 2005 || Minnesota || 11 || 19\t|| 25 || 44 || 53 || 2 || -- || -- || -- || -- || -- || --\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 2006 || Minnesota || 16 || 19 || 47 || 66 || 37 || 16 || 1 || 2 || 3 || 5 || 3 || 0\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| 2007 || Minnesota || 15 || 23 || 52 || 75 || 44 || 6 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 1 || 2 || 0\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 2008 || Minnesota || 16 || 33 || 36 || 69 || 56 || 10 || 1 || 0 || 3 || 3 || 1 || 0\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" \n| 2009 || Minnesota || 15 || 20 || 36 || 56 || 58 || 4 || -- || -- || -- || -- || -- || --\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 2010 || Edmonton || 16 || 31 || 43 || 74 || 33 || 2 || 2 || 3 || 12 || 15 || 7 || 0\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" \n| 2011 || Edmonton || 16 || 25 || 33 || 58 || 33 || 4 || -- || -- || -- || -- || -- || --\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 2012 || Edmonton || 16 || 19 || 38 || 57 || 38 || 4 || 3 || 10 || 11 || 21 || 4 || 0\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" \n| 2013 || Edmonton || 16 || 21 || 54 || 75 || 29 || 6 || 1 || 0 || 3 || 3 || 2 || 0\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 2014 || Philadelphia || 17 || 14 || 46 || 60 || 48 || 0 || -- || -- || -- || -- || -- || --\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"2\" | NLL Totals !! 17