ts|House Worcester 17]]\n[[Category:Worcester, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Leicester, Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "The '''17th Worcester district''' is one of 160 state [[Electoral district|legislative districts]] for the [[Massachusetts]] [[Massachusetts House of Representatives|House of Representatives]]. It is located in [[Central Massachusetts]].\n\n[[Massachusetts Democratic Party|Democrat]] [[David LeBoeuf]] of Worcester has represented the district since 2019.<ref>https://www.telegram.com/news/20181106/in-17th-worcester-district-leboeuf-claims-seat-back-for-democrats</ref>\n\n== District profile ==\nAs of the last redistricting in 2011<ref>https://malegislature.gov/Bills/187/H3770</ref>, the district encompasses all of the town of Leicester, including the villages of Cherry Valley and Rochdale, and the southwestern portion of the city of Worcester, including the neighborhoods of [[Main South]] and Webster Square.<ref>https://malegislature.gov/Legislators/Profile/DAL1/District</ref>\n\nLeicester is a small town and developing suburb.<ref>http://www.mapc.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Massachusetts-Community-Types-Summary-July_2008.pdf</ref> It contains the Leicester campus of [[Becker College]] and is over 90 percent [[Non-Hispanic whites|non-Hispanic white]]<ref>https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/leicestertownworcestercountymassachusetts/PST120218</ref> The Worcester portion of the district is an urban section of [[New England]]'s second largest city. It contains [[Clark University]] and has significant Latino, Asian, and Black communities.\n\n* [[Leicester, Massachusetts|Leicester]]\n* [[Worcester, Massachusetts|Worcester]]: Ward 7; and Precincts 2, 3, and 4 in Ward 8\n\n== District history ==\nAfter the 1973 redistricting, when the Massachusetts House of Representatives had 240 districts, the 17th Worcester district was located to the northeast of the city of Worcester, straddling [[Worcester County, Massachusetts|Worcester County]] and [[Middlesex County, Massachusetts|Middlesex County]].<ref>https://malegislature.gov/StateHouse/MediaGallery/Image/DistrictMap-House-1973-2.jpg</ref> The area is now split between the 12th Worcester, [[Massachusetts House of Representatives's 3rd Middlesex district|3rd Middlesex]], and 37th Middlesex districts.\n\n* [[Berlin, Massachusetts|Berlin]]\n* [[Bolton, Massachusetts|Bolton]]\n* [[Boxborough, Massachusetts|Boxborough]]\n* [[Harvard, Massachusetts|Harvard]]\n* [[Lancaster, Massachusetts|Lancaster]]\n* [[Northborough, Massachusetts|Northborough]]\n\n== Elections results from statewide races ==\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! width=\"30\" | Year\n! width=\"60\" | Office\n! width=\"180\" | Results\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2018\n| [[2018 Massachusetts gubernatorial election|Governor]]<ref>https://electionstats.state.ma.us/elections/view/131501/filter_by_county:Worcester</ref>\n| align=\"right\" {{party shading/Republican}} | [[Charlie Baker|Baker]] 64.2 \u2013 33.4%\n|-\n| [[2018 United States Senate election in Massachusetts|Senator]]<ref>https://electionstats.state.ma.us/elections/view/131505/filter_by_county:Worcester</ref>\n| align=\"right\" {{party shading/Democratic}} | [[Elizabeth Warren|Warren]] 57.4 \u2013 36.9%\n|-\n| 2016\n| [[2016 United States presidential election in Massachusetts|President]]<ref>https://electionstats.state.ma.us/elections/view/130243/filter_by_county:Worcester</ref>\n| align=\"right\" {{party shading/Democratic}} | [[Hillary Clinton|Clinton]] 57.4 \u2013 33.7%\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2014\n| [[2014 Massachusetts gubernatorial election|Governor]]<ref>https://electionstats.state.ma.us/elections/view/126084/filter_by_county:Worcester</ref>\n| align=\"right\" {{party shading/Republican}} | [[Charlie Baker|Baker]] 46.6 \u2013 45.9%\n|-\n| [[2014 United States Senate election in Massachusetts|Senator]]<ref>https://electionstats.state.ma.us/elections/view/126089/filter_by_county:Worcester</ref>\n| align=\"right\" {{party shading/Democratic}} | [[Ed Markey|Markey]] 58.9 \u2013 35.7%\n|-\n| 2013\n| [[2013 United States Senate special election in Massachusetts|Senator]]<ref>https://electionstats.state.ma.us/elections/view/124797/filter_by_county:Worcester</ref>\n| align=\"right\" {{party shading/Democratic}} | [[Ed Markey|Markey]] 50.1 \u2013 49.0%\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2012\n| [[2012 United States presidential election in Massachusetts|President]]<ref>https://electionstats.state.ma.us/elections/view/112698/filter_by_county:Worcester</ref>\n| align=\"right\" {{party shading/Democratic}} | [[Barack Obama|Obama]] 63.2 \u2013 34.1%\n|-\n| [[2012 United States Senate election in Massachusetts|Senator]]<ref>https://electionstats.state.ma.us/elections/view/112702/filter_by_county:Worcester</ref>\n| align=\"right\" {{party shading/Democratic}} | [[Elizabeth Warren|Warren]] 56.0 \u2013 42.9%\n|}\n\n== List of members representing the district ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! General<br/>Court\n! Representative\n! colspan=2 | Party\n! Term\n\n|-\n| 169th\n| nowrap | Robert Reynolds\n| style=\"background-color:{{Republican Party (United States)/meta/color}}\" | \n| Republican\n| 1975 \u2013 1977\n\n|-\n| 170th\n| nowrap | [[Walter Bickford]]\n| style=\"background-color:{{Democratic Party (United States)/meta/color}}\" | \n| Democratic\n| 1977 \u2013 1979\n\n|-\n| 171st\n| rowspan=3 | Robert McNeil\n| style=\"background-color:{{Democratic Party (United States)/meta/color}}\" | \n| rowspan=3 | Democratic\n| rowspan=3 | 1979 \u2013 1985\n\n|-\n| 172nd\n| style=\"background-color:{{Democratic Party (United States)/meta/color}}\" | \n\n|-\n| 173rd\n| style=\"background-color:{{Democratic Party (United States)/meta/color}}\" | \n\n|-\n| 174th\n| nowrap | William Donovan\n| style=\"background-color:{{Democratic Party (United States)/meta/color}}\" | \n| Democratic\n| 1985 \u2013 1987\n\n|-\n| 175th\n| rowspan=14 | [[John Binienda]]\n| style=\"background-color:{{Democratic Party (United States)/meta